I was faced with a deceptively simple task - how can a budding movie studio use EDA to make informed decisions about their movie-making process?

Having worked in the film and television industry for a number of years, my mind instantly went to all of the small production companies I had seen come and go.  Many only had the financial resources to pour everything into the success of a single film, only to go under when box office returns were not as fruitful as anticipated.  This was a purely hypothetical exercise involving a new studio under the Microsoft banner, so perhaps money wasn't as much of an object here.  Still, it remained in my mind throughout and I knew it should be explored further as I delved into the data.

## Datasets - Less is More

With 11 datasets to work with, it was important not to get overwhelmed and narrow my scope towards something that could be focused on and presented in a meaningful way.  Despite the appeal of Rotten Tomatoes data, I ended up using only The Numbers movie budgets dataset and two sets from the Internet Movie Database (IMDB).  I wanted to have a singular DataFrame to use for visualizations, and so began the cleaning process:

```
df_tn = pd.read_csv('zippedData/tn.movie_budgets.csv.gz')

df_tn['production_budget'] = df_tn['production_budget'].str.replace('$', '')
df_tn['production_budget'] = df_tn['production_budget'].str.replace(',', '')
df_tn['domestic_gross'] = df_tn['domestic_gross'].str.replace('$', '')
df_tn['domestic_gross'] = df_tn['domestic_gross'].str.replace(',', '')
df_tn['worldwide_gross'] = df_tn['worldwide_gross'].str.replace('$', '')
df_tn['worldwide_gross'] = df_tn['worldwide_gross'].str.replace(',', '')

df_tn['production_budget'] = df_tn['production_budget'].astype(int)
df_tn['domestic_gross'] = df_tn['domestic_gross'].astype(int)
df_tn['worldwide_gross'] = df_tn['worldwide_gross'].astype(int)
```

After checking for NaN values and dropping columns that I wouldn't used, I put together a final, merged DataFrame based on Return on Investment (ROI) to use as a central metric rather than domestic/worldwide gross or user rating (though I took a look at these as well):

```
df_complete['ROI'] = df_complete['worldwide_gross'] - df_complete['production_budget']
df_complete_roi_sorted = df_complete.sort_values('ROI', ascending=False).reset_index()
df_complete_roi_sorted.head(10)
df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes = df_complete_roi_sorted.groupby('movie').first()
df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes = df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes.sort_values('ROI', ascending=False).reset_index()
df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes = df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes.dropna().reset_index()
```

## The Visualizations Process

Ready to plot some visualizations, I had a look at the top 10 ROIs:

<img src="data:image/png;base64,%0A" width="900">

Not telling us too much that we may not have already known, I found similar results with studying both production budget and year of release when compared with ROI.  While ROI tended to generally increase over time, and as production budget increased, I decided to take a closer look at the genres of our top films.  Since my final DataFrame's "genres" column had several values separated by a comma, I used nested for loops to create a dictionary of each genre in the top 10% of ROIs and its count to then plot as a bar graph:

```
genre_dict = {}
for genres in df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes.head(210)['genres']:
    for genre in genres.split(','):
        if genre in genre_dict:
            genre_dict[genre] += 1
        else:
            genre_dict[genre] = 1
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(36,12))
ax = plt.bar(list(genre_dict.keys()), genre_dict.values(), color='r')
plt.title('Genre counts of top 10% of ROIs')
plt.xlabel('Genre')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()
```

<img src="data:image/png;base64,%0A" width="900">

The most successful genres here are Action and Adventure; yet when looking at the movie titles in the top ROIs ("Avatar," "Titanic," "The Avengers") - it seems obviously unlikely that a new studio (even, in theory, Microsoft) - would hit the ground running with movies of this caliber right away.  The next-highest genre, Comedy, seemed much more feasible and I wanted to have a look at some of the most successful movies of the genre, their budgets, and ROIs:

```
df_comedies = df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes.loc[df_complete_roi_sorted_no_dupes['genres'] == "Comedy"].sort_values('ROI', ascending=False).reset_index()
df_comedies = df_comedies.drop(['index', 'release_year', 'domestic_gross', 'runtime_minutes', 'averagerating', 'genres', 'numvotes'], axis=1)
df_comedies = df_comedies.set_index('movie')
df_comedies.head(10).plot(kind="bar", figsize=(24,12))
plt.title('Top 10 Comedies by ROI - Production Budgets and Worldwide Gross')
plt.xlabel('Movies')
plt.ylabel('Dollar Amount (in Hundreds of Millions)')
```

<img src="data:image/png;base64,%0A" width="900">

This felt like a better jumping off point for a new studio - more modest production budgets combined with generous worldwide gross and ROI.  At this point, some future work for the studio to consider would be identifying the creative teams behind some of these movies and possibly using them for future projects.

Finally, I wanted to quickly run through some of the IMDB user ratings to see what kinds of correlations existed.  Curious but without intending to put too much weight on these results, I rounded each rating to the nearest whole number and made a boxplot:

<img src ="data:image/png;base64,%0A" width="600">

Not surprisingly, the ROI tended to increase along with rating with the slight exception of the lowest rating of 1.  We might attribute this to users wanting to "balance out" a higher rating of a successful movie which they did not enjoy. There were very few outliers on the extremes of this spectrum and more in the 6 or 7 range.  It should follow that the studio should be mindful of the user experience during production and test screenings but not necessarily put too much into the difference between, say, a 6 and an 8.
